'''Arno Nadel''' (October 5, 1878 – March 1943) was a Jewish [[musicologist]], [[composer]], [[playwright]], [[poet]], and [[painter]].

== Early life ==
Nadel was born in [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]], (at the time of his birth, part of [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russia]]) to an [[Orthodox Jewish]] family.

== Career ==
In 1890, Nadel moved from Lithuania to Germany. At the age of 12, Nadel studied in [[Königsberg]], [[Germany]], under the cantor [[:de:Eduard Birnbaum|Eduard Birnbaum]]. He also studied with conductor and composer Robert Schwalm.<ref name=UnivHamburg-Bio>{{cite web|last1=Schipperge|first1=Thomas|title=Arno Nadel|url=http://www.lexm.uni-hamburg.de/object/lexm_lexmperson_00002835|website=[[Universität Hamburg]]|accessdate=27 July 2015|date=23 November 2010}}</ref>

In 1895, when he was 17 years old,<ref name=PaloAltoReview-TaoistPoetry>{{cite web|last1=Wasserman|first1=Martin|title=Arlo Nadel and His Taoist Poetry|url=http://www.accd.edu/pac/english/pareview/arlo.htm|website=Palo Alto Review|publisher=[[Palo Alto College]]|accessdate=27 July 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010911000615/http://www.accd.edu/pac/english/pareview/arlo.htm|archivedate=11 September 2001}}</ref> he moved to Berlin and enrolled in the [[Hochschule für die Wissenschaft des Judentums]]. He studied with composer Ludwig Mendelssohn and Max Lowengard.<ref name=UnivHamburg-Bio />

After graduating he worked at the Kottbusser Ufer Synagogue ([[:de:Synagoge Fraenkelufer|Synagoge am Kottbusser Ufer]]) as an educator and choirmaster. In 1916, he became choir director of the Jewish community of Berlin which included the supervision of music at all Berlin synagogues.<ref name=German-JewishMusic-Nadel-2013>{{cite book|editor1-last=Frühauf|editor1-first=Tina|title=German-Jewish Organ Music: An Anthology of Works from the 1820s to the 1960s|date=2013|publisher=A-R Editions, Inc.|location=Middleton, Wisconsin|ISBN=978-0-895-79761-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lh7X_rjAinoC&lpg=PR18&ots=DOQ0iPIula&dq=Robert%20Schwalm%20jewish&pg=PR18#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=27 July 2015|pages=xviii-xix|OCLC=830812812}}</ref>

Nadel was also a very prolific playwright and poet. Starting in 1918, Nadel took up painting as well, painting several self-portraits and biblical scenes.

In 1922, at the request of Jewish leadership, Nadel worked for years on an anthology of synagogue music, ''Kompendium Hallelujah! Gesänge für den jüdischen Gottesdienst'', which he finished in 1938 and intended to publish in seven volumes.<ref name=LBI-EricMandellCollection>{{cite web|title=Eric Mandell Collection, 1963-1964, AR 4408|url=http://access.cjh.org/1361613|website=[[Leo Baeck Institute]]|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=InternetArchive-Digitized-EricMandell>{{cite web|title=Eric Mandell Collection|url=https://www.archive.org/stream/ericmandellf001#page/n7/mode/1up|website=[[Internet Archive]]|accessdate=27 July 2015|page=40}}</ref><ref name=HebUnivJerusalem-Nadel-Bio>{{cite web|title=Arno Nadel|website=Jewish Music Research Centre|publisher=[[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]|url=http://www.jewish-music.huji.ac.il/content/arno-nadel|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>

Before he was deported, Nadel was able to leave his large collection of old Jewish [[liturgical]] materials with a non-Jewish neighbor,<ref name=PassportJewishMusic-1994>{{cite book|last1=Heskes|first1=Irene|title=Passport to Jewish Music: Its History, Traditions, and Culture|date=1994|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, Conn.|ISBN=978-0-313-38911-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WFpOGhL3qV8C&lpg=PA5&ots=6NPKNdpM3n&dq=eric%20mandell%20collection&pg=PA8#v=onepage&q=nadel&f=false|pages=7–8|accessdate=27 July 2015|OCLC=615600454}}</ref> some of which survived and were purchased by his friend Eric Mandell. What remains of these materials is held at [[Gratz College]] in Philadelphia.<ref name=WorldORT-Nadel-Bio>{{cite web|last1=Frühauf|first1=Tina|title=Arno Nadel|website=Music and the Holocaust|publisher=[[World ORT]]|url=http://holocaustmusic.ort.org/places/camps/central-europe/buchenwald/arno-nadel/|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Nadel was married to Beate Anna Nadel.<ref name=Bundesarchiv-MemorialBookBeate-2015>{{cite web|title=Nadel, Beate Anna – Memorial Book: Victims of the Persecution of Jews under the National Socialist Tyranny in Germany 1933–1945|url=https://www.bundesarchiv.de/gedenkbuch/en1122984|website=[[Bundesarchiv]]|accessdate=27 July 2015|date=4 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=YadVashem-Testimony-1998>{{cite web|last1=Lowey|first1=Ester|title=Page of Testimony: Arno Nadel|url=http://db.yadvashem.org/names/nameDetails.html?itemId=1411637&language=en|website=[[Yad Vashem]]|accessdate=27 July 2015|date=5 November 1998}}</ref>

He was a resident of [[Schöneberg]] quarter of Berlin. In November 1938, he was sent to the [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp]].<ref name=Bundesarchiv-MemorialBookArno-2015>{{cite web|title=Nadel, Arno – Memorial Book: Victims of the Persecution of Jews under the National Socialist Tyranny in Germany 1933–1945|url=https://www.bundesarchiv.de/gedenkbuch/en1123081|website=[[Bundesarchiv]]|accessdate=27 July 2015|date=4 February 2015}}</ref> Although Nadel was lucky enough to get papers to leave for England, he was too frail to make the trip. In March 1943, he and his wife were deported to the [[Auschwitz]] [[extermination camp]].<ref name=Bundesarchiv-MemorialBookArno-2015 /> He died there the same year.<ref name=WorldORT-Nadel-Bio /><ref name=Bundesarchiv-MemorialBookArno-2015 />

