[[File:Ccit 1951.jpg|thumb|The weighing curve of the CCIF 1951<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://realfield.com/anm/history/|title=The History of Low-Level Audio Background Noise Measurement|website=realfield.com|language=en-au|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>]] '''Psophometric voltage''' is a [[Electronic circuit|circuit]] noise [[voltage]] measured with a [[psophometer]] that includes a CCIF-1951<ref name=":0" /> [[weighting filter|weighting network]].
''"Psophometric voltage"'' should not be confused with ''"psophometric emf," i.e.'', the emf in a generator or [[line (electrical engineering)|line]] with 600 Ω internal resistance. For practical purposes, the psophometric emf is twice the corresponding psophometric voltage.
Psophometric voltage readings, ''V'', in millivolts, are commonly converted to [[dBm]](psoph) by dBm(psoph) = 20 log<sub>10</sub>''V''&nbsp;–&nbsp;57.78.
